   "week": 8,
   "abstract": "OpenStax explains socialization as the lifelong process by which people learn to be members of a society, taking on its norms, roles, and a sense of self through interaction rather than forming alone. The chapter uses the rare and disturbing cases of feral children, raised without human contact, to show how much of what seems natural about being human is actually learned in relationship. It also names agents of socialization, beginning with the family, that carry this work across the life course.",
   "coreIdea": "Who we are is learned in relationship through socialization, not formed alone, which is why a child raised without human contact never develops the ordinary human self.",
